"# Chapter 7 — Object-oriented programming — Simula, Smalltalk, C++

Object-oriented programming was a dominant paradigm in industry from
roughly 1990 to 2015. It's still very much in use. Its ideas —
bundles of data with attached functions, inheritance, polymorphism —
are now standard equipment in every mainstream imperative language.

But those ideas didn't start in the 1990s. They started decades
earlier.

## Simula — 1962 and 1967

Simula was designed by Ole-Johan Dahl and Kristen Nygaard at the
Norwegian Computing Center. Simula I (1962) was aimed at discrete-
event simulation — modeling systems like traffic, factories, or
telecommunications networks. Simula 67 (1967) generalized the ideas
into a general-purpose language.

Simula 67 introduced:
- **Classes**: templates for creating objects that bundle data with
  the procedures that act on the data.
- **Objects**: instances of classes, each with their own state.
- **Inheritance**: a subclass can specialize a superclass, adding
  new state and behavior.
- **Virtual procedures**: methods that get overridden by subclasses.

These are all standard features of object-oriented languages today.
Simula introduced them fifty-eight years ago and largely got them
right.

Simula never became commercially dominant. But it directly
influenced Smalltalk, C++, and through them essentially every OO
language since.

## Smalltalk — the pure vision

Smalltalk (Chapter 10 of Book of Language Ancestors covers Alan Kay)
was developed at Xerox PARC starting around 1972. Smalltalk-80
(1980) was the version that spread outside PARC.

Smalltalk's design was more radical than Simula's:
- **Everything** is an object. Even integers, characters, booleans.
- Objects communicate by **message-passing**. You don't 'call' an
  object's method; you 'send it a message.'
- Class definitions and method bodies are themselves objects; you
  can inspect and modify them at run-time.
- The whole system is written in itself. There's no boundary
  between the language and the environment.

Smalltalk was too radical for mainstream adoption. It required an
image-based development environment (you edit inside the running
system) that PC and Unix hackers of the 1980s weren't ready for. But
Smalltalk's ideas leaked out and shaped a lot.

## C++ — the compromise that took over

C++ was designed by Bjarne Stroustrup at Bell Labs starting in 1979.
Originally called 'C with Classes.' First C++ compiler shipped in
1985. Standardized in 1998, revised in 2003, 2011, 2014, 2017, 2020,
2023.

C++ was designed to add Simula-style object orientation to C without
losing C's efficiency. Objects are typically laid out as structs in
memory. Methods dispatch through a per-class table of function
pointers (the vtable). All of this compiles down to machine code
about as fast as equivalent C code.

C++ grew. And grew. It now includes:
- Classes with single and multiple inheritance
- Templates (parametric types)
- Exceptions
- Namespaces
- Smart pointers
- Move semantics
- Lambda expressions
- Concurrency primitives
- ... and much more

C++ is enormous. Its language spec runs to over 1500 pages. Different
teams use different subsets. Learning it fully takes years.

C++ is nonetheless dominant in game engines, high-performance
libraries, browsers, and other performance-critical work where C is
too low-level and Java-style managed languages are too slow.

## Java — the OO language for the masses

Java (Chapter 11) came out in 1995. It was Smalltalk's ideas in a
C-like package. Objects. Classes. Inheritance. Interfaces. Garbage
collection. A managed runtime that shields the programmer from
pointer bugs.

Java became the dominant OO language of the 2000s. Enterprise
applications, Android, big-data systems. Enormous. Java is still a
big language in industry.

## The OO ideas people talk about

- **Encapsulation**: bundle data and the code that manipulates it,
  hide the internal representation. Everything outside sees only the
  public interface.

- **Inheritance**: a class can extend another class. New class gets
  the parent's state and behavior, can override or add.

- **Polymorphism**: the same method call can behave differently
  depending on the object's actual class. A `draw` message sent to
  a Square draws differently than one sent to a Circle.

- **Composition**: an object can contain other objects. Sometimes
  contrasted with inheritance ('favor composition over inheritance'
  is a common advice).

Real OO code uses all of these. Whether it uses them well is a
different question.

## The OO critique

Object-oriented programming has been critiqued for various reasons:

- Deep inheritance hierarchies become hard to reason about.
- Mutable object state creates concurrency bugs.
- The 'mocking' problem — testing OO code often requires elaborate
  mock objects that don't match how the real system behaves.
- Some problems don't naturally decompose into objects and force
  awkward designs.
- Alan Kay himself said his original vision of OO (message-passing,
  late binding, everything an object) was not really what C++ or
  Java implement.

Nothing has replaced OO industrially, but functional programming
(Chapter 12) has taken back significant ground since the 2010s.
Most modern languages are multi-paradigm — OO plus functional plus
some other things.

## Scheme's answer

Scheme is not object-oriented in the C++/Java sense. Scheme has
closures, which can serve the same purposes as objects for many
problems:

```
(define (make-counter start)
  (let ((n start))
    (lambda (msg . args)
      (case msg
        ((get)       n)
        ((increment) (set! n (+ n 1)) n)
        ((reset)     (set! n start) n)))))

(define c (make-counter 10))
(c 'increment)   ;; => 11
(c 'get)         ;; => 11
```

That closure carries private state (`n`, `start`) and responds to
messages. It's a Smalltalk-flavored object built out of Scheme
primitives. This is one of the deep reasons Scheme keeps making
sense: with lambda and closures, you can build objects when you
want them, without the language forcing you into an object model.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Object-oriented programming is one way to organize code. It's been
enormously influential. It's not the only way. Functional programming
is another. Data-oriented programming is another. Each has its
strengths.

Motoi Scheme doesn't have classes. It has records and closures, which
can be composed into object-like things when needed. When someone
asks 'how do I define a class?' Motoi will explain the closure-based
alternative or the record-based alternative and let the person pick.

The industry's twenty-year love affair with OO taught us a lot,
both about what works and what doesn't. Most modern language designs
try to inherit the good ideas without the excesses.")
